title: Now reference Candidate_3.2.4 instead of master, replacing PR#47 (identical changes here)
body:
@jpgattuso

I've just closed Pull Request #47 (relative to your master branch) and issued a new request for the same changes but relative to your **Canditate_3.2.4** branch.

Here again is a brief global view of the changes (not all inclusive). Changes were made to *errors.R* and *derivnum.R** so that the user can specify the error on total boron (**eBt**) as a separate argument when calculating errors and so that seacarb users employ the latest defaults in the **epK** vector

The option to account for the error in total boron was offered in a previous pull request. Eventually though, you felt it was inappropriate to include that error at the end of the epK vector ('bor' is not an equilibrium constant after all). As a result, the current version of errors.R seacarb does not propagate any error for total boron. That deficiency would be remedied if you would accept this pull request. With this update, when calling errors.R, the user would specify the epK vector and eBt separately; otherwise the user accepts their defaults.

I've also changed the defaults for the epK vector (7 values for the 7 equil. constants) to those used in the most recent version of our manuscript. They have increased for K0, K1, and K2, following recommendations from A. Dickson (accounting for random and systematic errors). The updated valules are the same as specified in our Table 1. Likewise they are identical to the values used in the 3 other packages.

The corresponding documentation (.Rd files) have also been updated accordingly.

Thanks!

title: Refined derivnum.R & errors.R
body:
I have come across some bugs while making calculations and figures for our paper:

**derivnum.R:** 
- now correctly computes derivatives when any input is given as zero (var1, var2, T, S, Pt, Sit); before derivnum would return NaNs when any of this input was zero.  

**errors.R:** 
- changed default uncertainties of pKspa and pKspc from 0.01 to 0.02, following Mucci (1983)
- corrected sign error when calculating H+ uncertainty (it is now positive as are all other errors)
- logic to propagate error from Pt & Sit was complicated and flawed; it has now been simplified to be like that for all other input variables (after fixing derivnum to return the right results when either Pt or Sit are zero)

title: Removed the warning options that prevent compiling.
body:
Everything should now compile.  It turns out some of the new warning options in derivnum.R and errors.R prevented it from compiling.  I've removed those for now, so some warnings still show up when T or S are out of range (when calling one of those routines).  But overall things are much better, because most the warnings have been supressed.

This is all more complicated than I thought because in those 2 routines Jean-Marie has done some fancy programming to make local copies of some of the routines (e.g., for each of the constants) so he can perturb them in an efficient way (to calculate derivatives) without changing the carb routine.  But to do that, his local routines refer to the original seacarb routines in the "seacarb::" environment.  So I can't refer to a new 'warn' option in those older routines because they don't have it yet; they are not my updated versions.  

In short, everything should compile now and most of the warnings have been supressed. I'll talk to Jean-Marie when he returns from vacation to see what mght be done to supress the remaining warnings. This is not critical for now.

title: Added option to supress warnings; default is still to keep them.
body:
When using seacarb in Jupyter Notebooks (R kernel), i was getting hundreds of lines of warning messages every time that either T or S would be out of the valid range.  This occurs frequently for instance when trying to use the constants recommended for best practices in the Southern Ocean.  And I was getting a warning for each call to any of the constants routine (e.g., carb calls many of them by itself).  I understand that fewer warning messages show up in more routine  R interfaces, but with so many, it was making the presentation of my applications in Jupyter notebook completely unuseable.

So I added this simple option (warn="y" or "n") to each of the routines for each constant and those that call them.  Its a lot of routines, but the changes are very sipmle.  I've also updated the .Rd files accordingly. Now seacarb works perfectly in Jupyter Notebook (when I use warn="n").

Could you please merge this pull request into the master branch?

title: Added 3rd error method 'mo' with covariance term
body: To the errors.R routine, we've added a 3rd method called _method of moments_ ('mo'). It is  just like the _gaussian_ method except that it allows for covariance betweeen the 2 carbonate system variables.  The user has to specify the covariance with a regression coefficient 'r'.  By default that is zero.  The errors.Rd documentation file has also been modified to describe the 3rd approach. This new approach might be useful for example when pCO2 and pH are selected as the 2 input variables because they are often anti-correlated.

title: Added error propagation & numerical buffer factors; improved buffesm (bis)
body:
As requested, I have closed my pull request from yesterday (relative to seacarb-git's master branch), and opened a the same pull request but relative to seacarb-git's version-3.1-beta1 branch. Title of pull request and the comments below are essentially the same as before.

New routines have been added to perform error propagation (errors.R) and to take numerical derivatives (derivnum.R) of carb's calculated output variables with respect to its input variables and constants. An existing routine that computes buffer factors (buffesm.R) has been improved.

More specifically, this pull request concerns 2 new routines and 1 improved routine:
1. The `errors.R` routine allows the user to choose to use either the standard approach (Gaussian error propagation) or the Monte Carlo approach. Results of both approaches generally agree within 1% when the argument runs is set to 10 000 (samples).  But the Monte Carlo approach is more computationally intensive, requiring some seconds for each data point even at only runs=10000.  The Gaussian approach is the default.
2. The `derivnum.R` routine is useful not only because it is used in the error propagation (Gassian approach), but also because it computes partial derivatives of all output variables with respect to all input variables and constants; these sensitivities may also be referred to as buffer factors. The numerical approach has been refined to minimize error and its results agree extremely well with available analytical derivatives and mocsy's automatic derivatives which are as accurate as analytical derivatives. Thus the `derivnum` routine has been optimized and tested in many ways.
3. The 'buffesm.R' routine has been improved to account for effects of total dissolved inorganic phospphorus (Pt) and silicon (Sit) on buffer factors and the Revelle factor. This is an advance relative to the original equations from Egleston et al (2010) who did not acount for effects from these nutrients (Orr and Epitalon, 2015).

Jean-Pierre,

title: Fixed 'carb' output var indices, made consistent with seacarb 3.0+
body:
Jean-Pierre, 
In response to the email message by Xinping Hu, I've corrected buffesm.R in seacarb to give the right answers.  The carb routine is called within 'buffesm', but after changes to carb were made to accommodate several pCO2 and fCO2 variables (some time ago) I did not shift the index numbers within 'buffesm' for carb's output variables. I've now fixed 'buffesm', which no longer uses index numbers but rather just names of variables in the 'Carb' dataframe.  Thus we will avoid problems like this in the future, e.g., if variables or added to or removed from the carb dataframe. I also took advantage of this opportunity to make buffesm entirely consistent with the approach used in 'buffer.R', i.e., making the same updates as done for 'buffer.R' when making fixes earlier this year for inconsistencies due to the major revision of seacarb 3.0.
In addition, results from 'buffesm' now agree perfectly with those from buffer for the Revelle factor (R). Furthermore, they chack with results in Egleston et al. (2010, Fig. 2).

title: Fixed indices of 'carb' output in buffer.R
body: After my last change to carb.R where the number of output variables was incresed to include also fCO2insitu & pCO2insitu, the number of indices also increased.  This cause problems in 'buffer.R' because it called carb and then accessed its output with numerical indices. I have changed 'buffer.R' to solve this problem, using explicit names of output variables instead of numeric indices.  This change should also prevent similar problems if other variables are added to 'carb.R' at a later date.

title: carb.R - added "standard" as 3rd "gas" option for pCO2 input
buffer.R corrections (K0pot, pHscale, carb indices)
body:
Salut Jean-Pierre,

I was getting some very strange results for the Revelle factor with you latest version of seacarb (v3.0.4).  I have corrected the problems, and am rerunning data production for our paper.  In short, this new version of buffer.R has three changes
1) the K0 is computed with potential T and atm pressure only (K0pot);
2) the pH scale conversions are corrected as done previously in carb.R; and
3) indices for variables from carb have been corrected (they differ in new version of carb).

Cheers,

Jim

title: Fixes to ionic strength, pH scale conversion, fugfac, Ft etc.
Added potential fCO2 and pCO2 (fCO2pot, pCO2pot) as requested
body:
Jean-Pierre,

This is a first try to follow up on our conversation a couple of weeks ago, which concluded that we should add fCO2pot and pCO2pot to carb.R.  I think this modified carb.R works, based on a few quick tests. I'll know more in a few days once I compare these new seacarb results to mocsy.  While programming, I found that it was necessary to add a new option "gas" (as an input argument). That can be either 'potential' (the default) or 'insitu'.  It is required because for flags 21 to 25, pCO2 is an input variable and carb.R needs to know if that is potential pCO2 or in situ pCO2 in order to treat it correctly. Conversely, for the other flags, pCO2 and fCO2 are calculated so we don't need the 'gas' option.  Perhaps you could think of a better name for this option.

Cheers,

Jim
